1
00:01:05,640 --> 00:01:09,872
- OK. Let's do some business.
- Welcome to Washington, Harry.

2
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,356
Ed. I hate this town.
You know my sister's kid, JJ?

3
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:16,916
- Pleasure to see you...
- Don't give him a speech!

4
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:18,712
Talk to me. You set up the hotel?

5
00:01:18,840 --> 00:01:23,391
Everything is in order. Here's some
stuff by that reporter I told you about.

6
00:01:23,520 --> 00:01:25,476
Are you still going to make me
do that interview?

7
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:30,276
Look over this <i>New Republic</i> article
he wrote on the EEC.

8
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:33,233
He's not some do-gooder
with an axe to grind on my neck, is he?

9
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,430
You don't want a pushover, Harry.

10
00:01:35,560 --> 00:01:40,429
If Paul gives you the thumbs-up,
it's a big deal in this town.

11
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:42,278
Think he knows anything?

12
00:01:42,400 --> 00:01:45,358
God, no! That's why it's good for you
to meet him up front.

13
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:48,233
It shows you have nothing to hide.

14
00:01:50,520 --> 00:01:52,238
Uncle Harry.

15
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:54,557
Jesus Christ! Hey!

16
00:01:55,440 --> 00:01:57,590
- Billie!
- What?

17
00:01:57,720 --> 00:02:00,792
When a door opens on a plane,
you get out!

18
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:07,599
Move it!

19
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,076
They've arrived.

20
00:02:55,920 --> 00:02:58,912
Welcome to the Willard, Mr Brock.
I hope you had a pleasant journey.

21
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:04,353
Here he is. Remember, treat him nicely,
don't try to con him. Just be yourself.

22
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:07,517
- Paul! Good to see you again.
- Hello, Ed. How are you?

23
00:03:07,640 --> 00:03:10,154
No more hardnosed
investigative stuff, huh?

24
00:03:10,280 --> 00:03:12,748
Your man doesn't have
a problem with that, does he?

25
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:15,440
No! You're just
interviewing businessmen now.

26
00:03:15,560 --> 00:03:19,348
You know what they say, Ed.
The business of America is business.

27
00:03:19,480 --> 00:03:21,391
Harry Brock, this is Paul Verrall.

28
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:26,071
The writer. I know. I liked that thing
you did for the <i>New Republic</i> on the EEC.

29
00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:27,713
Well...

30
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:29,796
Thank you.

31
00:03:42,720 --> 00:03:45,075
The suite is newly remodelled,
the marble is Italian

32
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:47,509
and this wonderful glass
comes from the South of France.

33
00:03:47,640 --> 00:03:49,790
We're specially proud
of these atria,

34
00:03:49,920 --> 00:03:53,151
which give this suite
a lovely, open quality.

35
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:57,068
- I hope Mrs Brock is satisfied?
- She's not Mrs Brock.

36
00:03:57,200 --> 00:03:59,270
- That's fine.
- You bet it's fine.

37
00:03:59,400 --> 00:04:02,710
There's only one Mrs Brock
and she's my mother. And she's dead.

38
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:03,716
I'm sorry...

39
00:04:03,840 --> 00:04:05,637
Listen. Anybody that works in this room,

40
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:08,228
tell them to do it good,
do it fast, nobody gets hurt.

41
00:04:08,360 --> 00:04:11,193
I don't like a lot of people around,
and I don't like waiting.

42
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:13,151
Of course, Mr Brock.

43
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:15,874
- Like to save my life?
- With soda or plain water?

44
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:17,513
- Plain.
- Coming right up.

45
00:04:17,640 --> 00:04:20,632
- Paul, would you like a drink?
- I'm fine, Ed, thanks.

46
00:04:21,960 --> 00:04:23,757
- If there's anything I can do...
- There is.

47
00:04:23,880 --> 00:04:26,713
Go into Billie's room and see
she gets everything she wants.

48
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:30,549
She asks for somethin', I'm asking.
What about those white flowers?

49
00:04:30,680 --> 00:04:32,636
The gardenias? All taken care of.

50
00:04:32,760 --> 00:04:34,557
Did you get that other stuff?

51
00:04:34,680 --> 00:04:37,831
Diet cream soda, the bean dip,
tweezers and cucumber masks?

52
00:04:37,960 --> 00:04:41,509
- All taken care of.
- All right. JJ! Handle him.

53
00:04:41,640 --> 00:04:43,596
Chauncy! Over here.

54
00:04:45,280 --> 00:04:46,998
Billie!

55
00:04:48,240 --> 00:04:49,559
What?

56
00:04:49,680 --> 00:04:51,716
- Well?
- What?

57
00:04:51,840 --> 00:04:55,116
- Not bad, huh?
- Not bad.

58
00:04:55,240 --> 00:04:58,038
Not bad? You know
what this is costing me a night?

59
00:04:58,160 --> 00:05:00,196
$6,500, you already told me.

60
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:03,676
- So?
- So, I don't like new towns.

61
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:05,552
You have to learn
all new channels.

62
00:05:05,680 --> 00:05:08,274
It took me almost a minute
to find my soap!

63
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,798
So, what's this gonna be, pal?
A plug or a pan?

64
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:22,549
I like to know these things. Then I know
how to talk if I know your angle.

65
00:05:23,720 --> 00:05:26,234
No angle. Just the facts.

66
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:29,750
A pan. Listen, I gotta do my stairs
and stuff. Are you OK with that?

67
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:32,638
Sure.

68
00:05:32,760 --> 00:05:35,433
Good! JJ, get a barber up here
for when I get back.

69
00:05:35,560 --> 00:05:37,630
Grab my sweats, we're outta here.

70
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:41,119
I'm talking to you cos Ed told me to.

71
00:05:41,240 --> 00:05:43,834
I pay him a couple of hundred grand
a year for advice.

72
00:05:43,960 --> 00:05:45,791
I'd be a fool not to take it.

73
00:05:45,920 --> 00:05:47,273
Excuse me, mind if I...?

74
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:51,029
Anyway, go ahead.
Give me your best shot.

75
00:05:51,160 --> 00:05:53,276
How much money have you got?

76
00:05:54,360 --> 00:05:56,749
- What am I, an accountant?
- You don't know?

77
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:58,757
Not exactly.

78
00:05:58,880 --> 00:06:00,598
Fifty million?

79
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:02,039
Honest to God, I don't know.

80
00:06:02,160 --> 00:06:04,310
- Ten million?
- Maybe.

81
00:06:04,440 --> 00:06:05,953
- One million?
- More!

82
00:06:06,080 --> 00:06:09,311
- How much more?
- How much you got?

83
00:06:09,440 --> 00:06:10,953
I've saved a little.

84
00:06:11,080 --> 00:06:14,436
You don't save money, bud,
you make it!

85
00:06:15,960 --> 00:06:21,512
This is the worst time of day, after the
soaps but before <i>Entertainment Tonight.</i>

86
00:06:21,640 --> 00:06:24,552
I have some papers
for you to sign.

87
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:27,672
What happened to all that stuff
I signed yesterday?

88
00:06:28,840 --> 00:06:31,593
The back page of each set.
By the Xs.

89
00:06:31,720 --> 00:06:35,349
It seems like I signed
about 10,000 of these.

90
00:06:35,480 --> 00:06:39,029
That's what you get for being
a multiple corporate officer!

91
00:06:39,160 --> 00:06:40,878
Is that what I am?

92
00:06:41,840 --> 00:06:44,673
No wonder I'm having so much fun.

93
00:06:46,680 --> 00:06:50,798
Is it true you spent 400 million
on your new complex?

94
00:06:50,920 --> 00:06:54,959
Brock Village.
Finest thing ever built.

95
00:06:56,480 --> 00:06:59,870
2,000 condos, 175 shops...

96
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:04,198
...and two-count 'em-two
golf courses. My masterpiece.

97
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:09,348
- Did you have to take on a lot of debt?
- You gotta spend it to make it, pal.

98
00:07:18,440 --> 00:07:21,796
Not too vigorous, honey.
I get 'em done every day.

99
00:07:21,920 --> 00:07:23,990
Just buff 'em up real nice.

100
00:07:24,120 --> 00:07:26,270
How's the interview going?

101
00:07:26,400 --> 00:07:29,631
Oh, great!
I found out he has parents.

102
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:33,514
I still don't know
why he came to Washington.

103
00:07:33,640 --> 00:07:35,517
Just a little tax business.

104
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:39,635
I didn't believe him either.

105
00:07:39,760 --> 00:07:43,036
So far, I've been nice to you.
What are you pumping me for?

106
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:45,116
That's a reporter's work, Mr Brock.

107
00:07:45,240 --> 00:07:48,312
Who, what, when, where, how...

108
00:07:48,440 --> 00:07:50,351
...and why.
- Sounds like a law firm to me.

109
00:07:50,480 --> 00:07:55,429
- You know how much I hate lawyers.
- I can vouch for that!

110
00:07:55,560 --> 00:07:59,314
Are you ever afraid
that you're gonna lose all this?

111
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:01,795
Never. I want it all too much.

112
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:07,432
What about things that are
beyond your control, like... fate?

113
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:10,316
You show me a businessman
believes in fate,

114
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:13,034
I'll show you the first businessman
who ever went broke.

115
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:15,628
I started with a wagon,
selling somebody's junk.

116
00:08:15,760 --> 00:08:19,275
And I got here in a silk suit,
talking to a college know-it-all like you.

117
00:08:19,400 --> 00:08:23,473
If I lose it,
I'll meet you right back here in this room,

118
00:08:23,600 --> 00:08:26,194
in a new silk suit.

119
00:08:26,320 --> 00:08:28,197
Why would you lose it all, Mr Brock?

120
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:30,276
Hey, wait a minute!

121
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,797
Where do you think
you're going with that?

122
00:08:33,920 --> 00:08:35,797
- My room.
- Put it back.

123
00:08:35,920 --> 00:08:38,718
- I just wanted...
- Put it back.

124
00:08:39,400 --> 00:08:41,152
We have a party to go to.

125
00:08:41,280 --> 00:08:42,918
I don't see why I can't...

126
00:08:43,040 --> 00:08:46,032
Because I say you can't, that's why!
Put it back!

127
00:08:48,600 --> 00:08:51,433
Do what I'm tellin' you!

128
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:07,598
What'll you take to cut his throat,
barber?

129
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:11,673
Harry, don't get so upset...

130
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:15,316
Don't tell me what to do.

131
00:09:19,480 --> 00:09:22,119
You don't have to be so formal
around me, Harry!

132
00:09:22,240 --> 00:09:24,310
- Relax, be yourself.
- Excuse me.

133
00:09:24,440 --> 00:09:27,113
Uncle Harry, we gotta be
at the Duffees' at seven o'clock.

134
00:09:27,240 --> 00:09:29,595
Is that Alex Duffee,
the Secretary of the Navy?

135
00:09:29,720 --> 00:09:32,598
- JJ, would you get my briefcase?
- Sure, Ed.

136
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:36,872
Sorry about the blow-up.
Short fuse.

137
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:38,911
But I like talking to you.

138
00:09:39,040 --> 00:09:41,315
You make me laugh.

139
00:09:41,440 --> 00:09:43,317
Finally, a purpose in life.

140
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:48,035
- How about you working for me?
- Harry, I don't think...

141
00:09:48,160 --> 00:09:50,037
Did I ask you?

142
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:53,436
- Let the man answer.
- What would I do?

143
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:57,394
What do you care?
We'll find something for you.

144
00:10:00,560 --> 00:10:03,438
I don't think so, Mr Brock.
Thanks for the offer.

145
00:10:03,560 --> 00:10:07,030
- See you around, pal.
- Sure.

146
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:16,230
Not a bad guy for an egghead.
Send him a gift, a pen or something.

147
00:10:18,320 --> 00:10:20,436
You pissed at me?

148
00:10:20,560 --> 00:10:22,516
No.

149
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:26,956
You don't look right.
Want an aspirin?

150
00:10:27,440 --> 00:10:29,396
No, Harry, I'm fine.

151
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:35,069
Considering I've been dead for 12 years,
I feel great.

152
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:42,318
<i>Now with your abdominals</i>
<i>contracted, buttocks tight,</i>

153
00:10:42,440 --> 00:10:45,512
<i>you're going to be lifting the leg,</i>
<i>starting with the contraction.</i>

154
00:10:45,640 --> 00:10:47,631
<i>Here you go. And... contract.</i>

155
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:50,991
<i>And lift it. CP, OK?</i>

156
00:10:51,120 --> 00:10:55,750
<i>CL, contract and lift.</i>
<i>Contract and lift...</i>

157
00:11:03,240 --> 00:11:04,036
Hey!

158
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:08,438
- Tomorrow, we meet the lobbyists.
- I want congressmen... Billie!

159
00:11:09,160 --> 00:11:11,196
What?

160
00:11:11,320 --> 00:11:14,357
Hurry up. We're going down.
Meet you in the car.

161
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:16,956
JJ'll wait.

162
00:11:17,920 --> 00:11:19,876
I can't just phone Congress...

163
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:23,151
I leveraged my ass
to build Brock Village.

164
00:11:23,280 --> 00:11:26,636
If that base closes, I'm looking at
four million square feet of squat

165
00:11:26,760 --> 00:11:29,035
and I'm signing Chapter Eleven papers.

166
00:11:29,160 --> 00:11:32,914
Relax. That's the beauty of putting
the companies in Billie's name.

167
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:35,679
They can't be taken to settle any debts.

168
00:11:35,800 --> 00:11:38,394
Technically, they're not your companies.

169
00:11:44,360 --> 00:11:47,033
If I lose Brock Village, what's to say
I can't lose everything else?

170
00:11:47,160 --> 00:11:49,594
This is your fault! I want names.

171
00:11:49,720 --> 00:11:53,156
- Tomorrow, I've got lunch scheduled...
- Tonight, tonight!

172
00:11:53,280 --> 00:11:56,875
Tonight, you'll see Senator Hedges,
head of Appropriations.

173
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,070
He's behind in his fundraising
and his race is very tight.

174
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:01,316
- That's what I wanna hear.
- But Harry...!

175
00:12:02,320 --> 00:12:05,710
He's not a construction foreman.
The machinations required...

176
00:12:05,840 --> 00:12:09,594
Don't Harvard talk me. I didn't make
my money by being an idiot.

177
00:12:09,720 --> 00:12:10,948
Where the hell's Billie?

178
00:12:11,080 --> 00:12:13,036
Calm yourself, I'm here.

179
00:12:13,160 --> 00:12:16,869
- Does she look OK to you?
- What's the matter with how I look?

180
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:18,956
- That's what I wanna know.
- What do you know?

181
00:12:19,080 --> 00:12:21,116
You open beer cans with your teeth!

182
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:23,071
- You look beautiful, Billie.
- Thank you, Ed.

183
00:12:23,200 --> 00:12:25,509
Are you sure?
I don't wanna start off on no left foot.

184
00:12:25,640 --> 00:12:30,077
- I'm sure, I'm sure.
- That's OK. That's beautiful!

185
00:12:35,480 --> 00:12:37,436
JJ, you stay here.

186
00:12:41,960 --> 00:12:44,474
- Good evening, Alex!
- Hi, Ed. How are you?

187
00:12:44,600 --> 00:12:48,388
- May I introduce my friend...
- Harry Brock, nice to meet you.

188
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:50,272
And Miss Billie Dawn.

189
00:12:50,400 --> 00:12:54,313
What a beautiful name!
This is my wife, Beatrice.

190
00:12:54,440 --> 00:12:55,668
Hello, how are you?

191
00:12:55,800 --> 00:12:57,597
Charmed!

192
00:12:57,720 --> 00:12:59,073
Hi, nice to meet you.

193
00:12:59,200 --> 00:13:00,838
Hello, Bea.

194
00:13:00,960 --> 00:13:03,190
Senator Dorn and his wife Lilly...

195
00:13:03,320 --> 00:13:07,108
Senator, Harry Brock,
pleasure to meet you. Hi.

196
00:13:07,240 --> 00:13:09,231
And Senator and Mrs Hedges.

197
00:13:09,360 --> 00:13:11,794
Senator, good to see you.

198
00:13:11,920 --> 00:13:13,751
Billie, this is Senator Hedges.

199
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:16,030
Yeah, that's what he said.

200
00:13:17,240 --> 00:13:21,233
- What brings you to town?
- Sightseeing, taking it easy.

201
00:13:21,360 --> 00:13:23,635
Oh, that'll be the day!

202
00:13:25,640 --> 00:13:27,710
I'm a little dry.
Care to join me for a drink?

203
00:13:27,840 --> 00:13:30,479
Excuse us, ladies. Alex.

204
00:13:41,360 --> 00:13:45,638
- It's so screwed up I can't do...
- Mr Brock! Good to see you again.

205
00:13:45,760 --> 00:13:48,513
What a coincidence, hey, Sherlock?

206
00:13:48,640 --> 00:13:52,076
- How's it going?
- I'm off duty. My meter ain't running.

207
00:13:52,200 --> 00:13:54,714
- Billie's here from Chicago.
- Really?

208
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:57,308
I got my doctorate from
the University of Chicago.

209
00:13:57,520 --> 00:14:00,876
I just interviewed your mayor.
I have a radio show.

210
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,150
What are you planning to see
while you're here?

211
00:14:03,280 --> 00:14:04,554
I don't really know.

212
00:14:04,680 --> 00:14:08,070
Since I've never been here before,
I don't know what there is to see.

213
00:14:08,200 --> 00:14:10,668
What kinds of things are you interested in?

214
00:14:11,680 --> 00:14:16,196
- Maybe something with the Kennedys.
- You could go to the Kennedy Center.

215
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:22,953
No, I'd like to see their house, go
on one of them tours, like Graceland.

216
00:14:23,080 --> 00:14:26,914
You learn a lot about a person
when you see their home.

217
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:30,589
Did you know
that Elvis had over 40 TVs?

218
00:14:30,720 --> 00:14:32,836
I mean, when I saw that,

219
00:14:32,960 --> 00:14:35,838
I knew that Elvis must have been
a really lonely man.

220
00:14:35,960 --> 00:14:38,838
They say it on the tour,
about the 40 TVs,

221
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:42,635
like it was a big thing,
like you should be jealous of Elvis.

222
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:45,752
But it just made me really sad.

223
00:14:45,880 --> 00:14:47,757
Everybody in the world
worshipped Elvis,

224
00:14:47,880 --> 00:14:51,634
and it was like he couldn't be
in a room alone. You know?

225
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:54,991
- I mean, that's sad, don't you think?
- Well...

226
00:14:55,120 --> 00:14:56,792
Kennedy lived in the White House.

227
00:14:56,920 --> 00:15:01,436
Oh, yeah, well, that would be great
if I could see right in there.

228
00:15:01,560 --> 00:15:04,358
If you do decide to take a tour,
my husband can help.

229
00:15:04,480 --> 00:15:08,439
- He's the Under-Secretary of Commerce.
- Is that like a receptionist?

230
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:12,679
Isn't a receptionist
under a secretary?

231
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:16,270
Well, he certainly feels that way
sometimes!

232
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:21,516
I think I need to freshen this up.
Is everyone else all right?

233
00:15:21,640 --> 00:15:23,153
I could use another one.

234
00:15:23,280 --> 00:15:26,590
- What about you, Billie?
- No, thank you.

235
00:15:37,120 --> 00:15:39,680
Something I said was wrong, wasn't it?

236
