00:31:35,280 --> 00:31:37,510
Sucker.
You coulda gotten twice that.

478
00:31:37,640 --> 00:31:39,756
He's got a lot of it, you know.

479
00:31:40,840 --> 00:31:43,229
I'd have done it for nothing.

480
00:31:44,680 --> 00:31:47,353
Even if I am stupid,
it hasn't hurt me none.

481
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:51,278
- What do you mean?
- I've got everything that I want.

482
00:31:52,160 --> 00:31:54,549
I got lots of jewels, big like I like.

483
00:31:54,680 --> 00:31:56,238
Mink coat.

484
00:31:56,360 --> 00:31:58,920
A TV that fits in my purse.

485
00:31:59,040 --> 00:32:01,110
I want something, I ask for it.

486
00:32:01,240 --> 00:32:02,832
If he don't give me what I want,

487
00:32:02,960 --> 00:32:06,919
I don't give him what he wants.
If you get my drift?

488
00:32:08,160 --> 00:32:10,071
And you're happy with this setup?

489
00:32:10,200 --> 00:32:13,510
So long as I know how to get what I want,
that's all I want to know.

490
00:32:13,640 --> 00:32:15,312
Makes sense.

491
00:32:15,440 --> 00:32:18,512
So long as you know
what it is you want.

492
00:32:18,640 --> 00:32:20,517
Exactly.

493
00:32:20,640 --> 00:32:21,789
What?

494
00:32:21,920 --> 00:32:24,673
Well, I mean, if you don't know a lot,

495
00:32:25,480 --> 00:32:28,392
how do you know that a mink coat
is the best thing to have?

496
00:32:28,520 --> 00:32:31,592
Because I used to have
a rabbit coat.

497
00:32:36,680 --> 00:32:39,035
I love this song.

498
00:32:39,160 --> 00:32:41,037
Let's dance.

499
00:32:41,160 --> 00:32:43,549
Oh, I don't... I can't dance.

500
00:32:43,680 --> 00:32:46,513
I can.
Harry and me won a medal once.

501
00:32:46,640 --> 00:32:49,473
Well, this isn't a dancing place.

502
00:32:49,600 --> 00:32:51,716
It is if you're dancing. Come on.

503
00:32:56,840 --> 00:33:00,196
<i>We'll start with the ABC of it</i>

504
00:33:02,520 --> 00:33:05,910
<i>Then we'll roll down</i>
<i>to the XYZ of it</i>

505
00:33:06,040 --> 00:33:07,996
Relax.

506
00:33:08,400 --> 00:33:11,233
<i>Help me solve the mystery of it...</i>

507
00:33:14,800 --> 00:33:20,033
OK, so, we should make a list
of things you would like to do and...

508
00:33:21,920 --> 00:33:23,876
...and, er...

509
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:31,388
<i>And if a shooting star rolls by</i>

510
00:33:32,440 --> 00:33:37,230
<i>I'll use that star to write "I love you"</i>

511
00:33:38,720 --> 00:33:42,235
<i>A thousand times, across the sky</i>

512
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:45,558
<i>One thing isn't very clear, my love</i>

513
00:33:48,400 --> 00:33:51,949
<i>Should the teacher</i>
<i>stand so near, my love?</i>

514
00:33:53,960 --> 00:33:57,589
<i>Graduation's almost here, my love</i>

515
00:33:58,240 --> 00:34:02,279
<i>Oh, yeah, yeah, teach me tonight</i>

516
00:34:05,160 --> 00:34:08,118
Maybe I could teach you something.

517
00:34:08,240 --> 00:34:11,915
<i>... a blackboard high above you</i>

518
00:34:12,680 --> 00:34:16,559
<i>And if an astronaut zooms by</i>

519
00:34:18,160 --> 00:34:20,310
<i>I'll reach and grab him real fast</i>

520
00:34:20,440 --> 00:34:22,795
<i>Then write "I love you"...</i>

521
00:34:24,040 --> 00:34:25,917
Well, OK...

522
00:34:26,040 --> 00:34:28,395
Good night, Miss Dawn.

523
00:34:28,520 --> 00:34:30,954
And... thanks! That was fun.

524
00:34:32,480 --> 00:34:35,438
Aren't you gonna
escort me to my room?

525
00:34:37,320 --> 00:34:40,630
- Yeah... Sure, of course.
- You can call me Billie.

526
00:34:40,760 --> 00:34:42,716
Billie.

527
00:34:43,520 --> 00:34:45,670
It's funny, you don't look like a Billie.

528
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:47,711
No?

529
00:34:47,840 --> 00:34:49,796
Do I look like an Emma?

530
00:34:50,200 --> 00:34:52,395
- Emma?
- Yeah. That's my real name.

531
00:34:52,520 --> 00:34:54,476
I took Billie for Vegas.

532
00:34:55,880 --> 00:34:58,189
No. You don't look like...

533
00:34:58,320 --> 00:35:00,834
I mean, you don't look like an Emma either!

534
00:35:01,640 --> 00:35:03,278
What do I look like?

535
00:35:03,400 --> 00:35:05,197
To me?

536
00:35:05,320 --> 00:35:07,356
Yeah, to you.

537
00:35:10,600 --> 00:35:12,033
Like an angel.

538
00:35:13,200 --> 00:35:15,156
Sweet talk, again!

539
00:35:17,720 --> 00:35:19,676
Well...

540
00:35:28,320 --> 00:35:30,197
OK! Good night, Billie.

541
00:35:30,320 --> 00:35:35,553
Paul, are you a talker or would you
be interested in a little action?

542
00:35:37,680 --> 00:35:41,229
- Excuse me?
- I got the hots for you right off.

543
00:35:42,360 --> 00:35:45,432
Well... do you get many?

544
00:35:45,760 --> 00:35:47,637
Now and then.

545
00:35:47,760 --> 00:35:52,117
- What do you do about them?
- Stick around and you'll find out!

546
00:35:54,280 --> 00:35:55,998
What about...?

547
00:35:56,120 --> 00:36:00,272
Don't worry about him.
He's too busy being a big man.

548
00:36:02,920 --> 00:36:05,115
This isn't what I expected!

549
00:36:05,240 --> 00:36:08,869
We're just teaching each other
what we know.

550
00:36:10,560 --> 00:36:12,949
Yes, well, about that...

551
00:36:13,080 --> 00:36:18,632
Just read these papers and circle
anything you don't understand.

552
00:36:18,760 --> 00:36:20,637
I don't know about that.

553
00:36:20,760 --> 00:36:23,399
My eyes are kind of weak.

554
00:36:24,040 --> 00:36:27,112
Really?
Well, maybe you oughta try some glasses.

555
00:36:27,240 --> 00:36:29,196
And look like a geek?

556
00:36:33,160 --> 00:36:35,116
I'm sorry.

557
00:36:37,640 --> 00:36:39,596
Th-that's OK.

558
00:37:05,920 --> 00:37:08,673
Course, they're not so bad on men.

559
00:37:09,240 --> 00:37:11,037
No?

560
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:18,588
How're you guys making out?

561
00:37:18,720 --> 00:37:20,915
Oh, fine.

562
00:37:21,040 --> 00:37:23,918
Paul just... taught me a little French!

563
00:37:24,040 --> 00:37:26,679
Is that right, pal? What's the matter?

564
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:30,076
Was she rude to you?
She's got a mouth on her.

565
00:37:30,200 --> 00:37:32,156
Yes, I know that!

566
00:37:33,280 --> 00:37:36,750
Well, I'm gonna say good night.
Good night!

567
00:37:38,200 --> 00:37:40,156
Wait a minute, buddy.

568
00:37:41,960 --> 00:37:44,190
What's the matter with you?

569
00:37:46,240 --> 00:37:49,596
Where's your manners?
Say thank you to the guy.

570
00:37:49,720 --> 00:37:51,676
Oh... yeah.

571
00:37:56,800 --> 00:37:58,756
<i>Au revoir.</i>

572
00:38:00,280 --> 00:38:01,679
Good night, Billie.

573
00:38:01,800 --> 00:38:03,756
Night.

574
00:38:06,480 --> 00:38:09,040
That guy could do you a lotta good.

575
00:38:10,280 --> 00:38:11,315
I agree.

576
00:38:29,600 --> 00:38:32,068
How'd you know it was me?

577
00:38:32,200 --> 00:38:34,111
Lucky guess.

578
00:38:34,240 --> 00:38:38,119
- Hi. Are you having lunch?
- Just a cappuccino, thanks.

579
00:38:39,480 --> 00:38:43,155
This is ridiculous. It looks like
the paper has the chicken pox.

580
00:38:43,280 --> 00:38:46,716
It would have been easier if you'd told me
to circle things I knew.

581
00:38:46,840 --> 00:38:49,798
I'm never gonna be able
to talk to anybody in this town.

582
00:38:49,920 --> 00:38:52,832
I brought something along
that may help you.

583
00:38:52,960 --> 00:38:56,316
Somebody who's really smart
and looks just like me?

584
00:38:57,960 --> 00:39:00,758
You want to be able to talk to people
in this town?

585
00:39:00,880 --> 00:39:04,998
In Washington, everybody says
exactly the same things at every party.

586
00:39:05,120 --> 00:39:07,076
You just have to know
the right responses.

587
00:39:07,200 --> 00:39:10,954
If you learn these eight sentences,
you'll be a hit at every party.

588
00:39:11,080 --> 00:39:12,752
- You're kidding me!
- Nope.

589
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:17,032
Those eight sentences cover just about
everything anybody talks about.

590
00:39:17,160 --> 00:39:18,479
It's the Washington art

591
00:39:18,600 --> 00:39:22,229
of sounding like you know what you're
talking about when you don't know zip.

592
00:39:22,360 --> 00:39:25,193
- Go ahead. Read the first.
- OK.

593
00:39:26,600 --> 00:39:30,275
"Here's what I'd like to know; who
elected the Washington Post president?"

594
00:39:30,400 --> 00:39:33,995
That one applies
about 80 per cent of the time.

595
00:39:34,120 --> 00:39:36,953
Number two. "We can't be
the policemen of the world,

596
00:39:37,080 --> 00:39:41,471
but until we get another cop on the
block, we have to support our friends."

597
00:39:41,600 --> 00:39:44,433
That one comes up a lot.
Number three.

598
00:39:44,560 --> 00:39:47,472
"Being a superpower has a price."

599
00:39:47,600 --> 00:39:50,956
Use that with number two
and number four. Read number four.

600
00:39:51,080 --> 00:39:52,718
"It's still a dangerous world."

601
00:39:52,840 --> 00:39:56,150
I'm just gonna say these things
and I'm gonna be a hit?

602
00:39:56,280 --> 00:40:00,034
Yeah, but you have to say them
at the right time.

603
00:40:00,160 --> 00:40:01,991
Read number five.

604
00:40:02,120 --> 00:40:05,510
"That's about as likely
as a Democrat being elected president."

605
00:40:05,640 --> 00:40:08,393
That one shows
you have a sense of humour.

606
00:40:08,520 --> 00:40:10,317
That was funny?

607
00:40:11,600 --> 00:40:13,477
Number six.

608
00:40:13,600 --> 00:40:16,956
"It makes you wonder if a par...
parli..."

609
00:40:17,080 --> 00:40:18,957
Parliamentary.

610
00:40:19,080 --> 00:40:23,232
"...system isn't better."
Yeah, the whole thing makes me wonder!

611
00:40:23,360 --> 00:40:25,237
Number seven.

612
00:40:25,360 --> 00:40:29,558
"I don't think Abe Lincoln himself
would know what to do about that."

613
00:40:29,680 --> 00:40:32,319
You say that one
when you don't know what to say.

614
00:40:32,440 --> 00:40:35,398
Oh, good! Then I'll just say that one.

615
00:40:38,760 --> 00:40:43,470
Number eight is when you're trapped
and you want to shut someone up.

616
00:40:43,600 --> 00:40:49,436
"If only the UN would take out the
Verner Amendment to Resolution 165,

617
00:40:49,560 --> 00:40:52,836
we'd have the power
to do what needs to be done."

618
00:40:53,240 --> 00:40:55,310
I don't understand one word of that.

619
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:59,237
No-one will.
There is no Verner Amendment.

620
00:40:59,360 --> 00:41:02,272
But the only time anyone in Washington
admits they don't know something

621
00:41:02,400 --> 00:41:04,630
is when they're being indicted.

622
00:41:04,760 --> 00:41:07,638
But how am I going to know
when to say which one?

623
00:41:07,760 --> 00:41:10,479
We'll work out a code. OK?

624
00:41:16,880 --> 00:41:21,158
Try not to talk to anyone. This guy's
only been working on you for a day.

625
00:41:21,280 --> 00:41:24,272
She can talk to anybody, Harry,
and make you proud.

626
00:41:24,400 --> 00:41:25,799
It's working backwards!

627
00:41:25,920 --> 00:41:29,435
Instead of making her smart,
she's making you stupid.

628
00:41:30,440 --> 00:41:31,998
Good evening.

629
00:41:45,120 --> 00:41:49,193
The Middle East is a money drain!
Lt'll always be the same.

630
00:41:49,320 --> 00:41:51,470
We ought to spend that money at home.

631
00:41:51,600 --> 00:41:53,477
So just ignore the region?

632
00:41:54,280 --> 00:41:59,400
Miss Dawn, is there a chance
for peace in the Middle East?

633
00:42:01,480 --> 00:42:05,837
The chances are as good as getting
a Democrat back in the White House.

634
00:42:07,160 --> 00:42:10,311
After all the problems
the President's had recently,

635
00:42:10,440 --> 00:42:12,476
he doesn't have much clout anyway.

636
00:42:15,200 --> 00:42:18,670
It makes you wonder
if a parliamentary system isn't better.

637
00:42:18,800 --> 00:42:22,110
But I think we should keep a strong
presence over there, don't you?

638
00:42:23,520 --> 00:42:25,238
Well, here's what I have to say.

639
00:42:25,360 --> 00:42:27,874
Who elected the <i>Washington Post</i>
king of the universe?

640
00:42:29,160 --> 00:42:33,438
- Excuse me.
- I'm sorry, what did you say?

641
00:42:33,560 --> 00:42:36,154
Do you think we should keep
an active presence over there?

642
00:42:36,280 --> 00:42:38,953
Forgive me! I thought you said...

643
00:42:39,080 --> 00:42:41,514
Anyway, active presence, yeah...

644
00:42:41,640 --> 00:42:42,868
Well...

645
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:46,754
I know we can't be
the policemen of the world,

646
00:42:46,880 --> 00:42:51,590
but until we get another cop, we have
an obligation to support our friends.

647
00:42:52,880 --> 00:42:56,077
After all,
being a superpower has its price.

648
00:42:56,200 --> 00:42:57,474
She's right.

649
00:42:59,080 --> 00:43:01,435
It's still a dangerous world.

650
00:43:01,560 --> 00:43:04,313
But what about the Palestinians?

651
00:43:04,440 --> 00:43:09,116
- Yes, what about the Palestinians?
- Yeah, what about the Palestinians?

652
00:43:10,600 --> 00:43:13,751
I don't think even Abe Lincoln himself
could solve that one.

653
00:43:13,880 --> 00:43:17,998
- But let's say you're president.
- Yeah, let's say you was president.

654
00:43:18,120 --> 00:43:19,997
What would you do?

655
00:43:20,120 --> 00:43:25,274
It's simple. If the UN would remove the
Verner Amendment from Resolution 165,

656
00:43:25,400 --> 00:43:27,994
we'd have the authority
to do what needs to be done.

657
00:43:30,800 --> 00:43:33,189
Can I get anyone anything?

658
00:43:33,320 --> 00:43:35,754
I'd love a drink.

659
00:43:37,400 --> 00:43:39,277
Excuse us.

660
00:43:39,400 --> 00:43:41,118
Isn't she terrific?

661
00:43:41,240 --> 00:43:42,958
Hell, I'm knocked out.

662
00:43:43,080 --> 00:43:46,038
- She's right about the Verner Amendment.
- Absolutely.

663
00:43:46,160 --> 00:43:49,596
Is it the economy of the state
that worries you, Harry, or your own?

664
00:43:49,720 --> 00:43:53,349
Both. If I go under,
I take a lot of people with me.

665
00:43:53,480 --> 00:43:55,675
Harry, I'm getting tired.

666
00:43:55,800 --> 00:43:57,677
I got business.

667
00:43:57,800 --> 00:44:00,189
Do me a favour, pal, take her home?

668
00:44:00,320 --> 00:44:02,276
With pleasure.

669
00:44:06,400 --> 00:44:08,755
You did a helluva job.

670
00:44:08,880 --> 00:44:11,440
No kiddin', pal. A helluva job.

671
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:20,757
Senator, we cannot do a thing until
the UN removes the Verner Amendment.

672
00:44:20,880 --> 00:44:23,952
- Yeah, 165!
- Without question.

673
00:44:26,080 --> 00:44:27,957
You were great!

674
00:44:28,080 --> 00:44:30,036
Everybody loved you.

675
00:44:32,320 --> 00:44:35,676
What's the matter?
Don't you think you were great?

676
00:44:35,800 --> 00:44:38,633
Oh, yeah, we really tricked 'em,
didn't we?

677
00:44:40,080 --> 00:44:41,638
What do you mean?

678
00:44:41,760 --> 00:44:46,311
If you saw a good ventriloquist, who
would you compliment? The dummy?

679
00:44:48,960 --> 00:44:50,678
You're not a dummy.

680
00:44:50,800 --> 00:44:53,360
Harry's right.
You're the one who did it.

681
00:44:54,200 --> 00:44:57,590
I still don't know anything,
only now nobody can tell.

682
00:45:00,440 --> 00:45:04,479
But Paul, there was one time,
right in the middle,

683
00:45:04,600 --> 00:45:07,637
when I was saying something
and everybody was looking at me,

684
00:45:07,760 --> 00:45:10,479
like I knew what I was talking about!

685
00:45:11,560 --> 00:45:13,516
And I liked it so much!

686
00:45:17,400 --> 00:45:20,119
Did you teach me to cheat
cos you think I can't learn?

687
00:45:21,680 --> 00:45:23,352
Oh, God, Billie, no!

688
00:45:23,480 --> 00:45:27,473
I... I just didn't think
you were so serious about it.

689
00:45:29,600 --> 00:45:32,034
I'm kind of surprised myself.

690
00:45:33,360 --> 00:45:36,716
I've been thinking a lot
about something my dad used to say.

691
00:45:36,840 --> 00:45:41,197
"Without knowledge,
you are less than everybody."

692
00:45:41,320 --> 00:45:43,197
And I don't want to be less.

693
00:45:43,320 --> 00:45:46,039
I don't want be better than anybody
neither,

694
00:45:46,160 --> 00:45:48,390
and I don't want to go above myself.

695
00:45:48,520 --> 00:45:50,476
I just want...

696
00:45:51,280 --> 00:45:53,840
I want to not be less.

697
00:45:56,120 --> 00:45:59,351
Well, I'm afraid
it's too late for that.

698
00:46:07,080 --> 00:46:09,833
Cos you're already
more than most people.

699
00:46:15,720 --> 00:46:17,358
Well, here we are.

700
00:46:17,480 --> 00:46:20,313
See you tomorrow?

701
00:46:21,360 --> 00:46:24,113
So, how are we gonna smarten me up?

702
00:46:24,960 --> 00:46:27,474
Well, we aren't gonna do it.

703
00:46:27,600 --> 00:46:30,910
You're gonna do it.
It's your battle.

704
00:46:31,920 --> 00:46:33,876
It's up to you.

705
00:46:35,760 --> 00:46:37,557
Good night.

706
00:46:37,680 --> 00:46:39,636
G'night.

707
00:47:05,960 --> 00:47:08,190
What are you reading?

708
00:47:08,320 --> 00:47:11,039
<i>Democracy In America</i> by...

709
00:47:12,440 --> 00:47:14,192
...Pocahontas.

710
00:47:15,120 --> 00:47:17,076
Yeah, she's good.

711
00:47:49,680 --> 00:47:51,830
What's anachronistic?

712
00:47:54,520 --> 00:47:56,238
Dictionary.

713
00:47:56,360 --> 00:47:58,316
It's a dictionary?

714
00:47:58,560 --> 00:48:01,950
No, look it up... in the dictionary.

715
00:48:04,600 --> 00:48:06,670
Jeez, that's a book?

716
00:48:06,800 --> 00:48:09,837
It's bigger than my first apartment.

717
00:49:04,160 --> 00:49:05,832
Billie, what are you doing?

718
00:49:05,960 --> 00:49:09,111
I don't like this!
I don't like this at all!

719
00:49:09,240 --> 00:49:11,708
Every word in there, I don't understand!

720
00:49:11,840 --> 00:49:14,308
I had to go to the dictionary
so many times,

721
00:49:14,440 --> 00:49:16,829
people must have thought I was foreign!

722
00:49:16,960 --> 00:49:20,350
This whole thing is making me
feel dumber, not smarter!

723
00:49:20,480 --> 00:49:23,438
I've been reading this for a week
and I'm on page 13!

724
00:49:23,560 --> 00:49:25,152
Well, that's not so bad.

725
00:49:25,280 --> 00:49:28,033
Not if the book's 14 pages, it's not!

726
00:49:28,480 --> 00:49:32,598
It's not supposed to go fast,
it's supposed to make you think.

727
00:49:32,720 --> 00:49:37,475
Yeah, it makes you think how great
it would be to sit around and watch TV!

728
00:49:37,600 --> 00:49:40,273
I don't want to do this any more. I quit!

729
00:49:40,400 --> 00:49:42,277
Billie! Wait a minute.

730
00:49:42,400 --> 00:49:46,757
Being smart isn't just about books.
It's about asking questions.

731
00:49:46,880 --> 00:49:50,350
It's about finding out
why things are the way they are.

732
00:49:50,480 --> 00:49:52,755
Don't stop reading.

733
00:49:52,880 --> 00:49:56,077
But you picked
a kind of a big book to begin with.

734
00:49:57,200 --> 00:50:00,192
How about starting with
something a little smaller?

735
00:50:01,280 --> 00:50:03,794
Like what? A fortune cookie?

736
00:50:22,360 --> 00:50:25,557
- This just came for you.
- Thanks.

737
00:50:53,920 --> 00:50:56,753
<i>Did you say</i>
<i>I've got a lot to learn?</i>

738
00:50:57,920 --> 00:51:01,435
<i>But don't think</i>
<i>I'm trying not to learn</i>

739
00:51:01,560 --> 00:51:04,597
<i>Since this is</i>
<i>a perfect spot to learn</i>

740
00:51:05,480 --> 00:51:07,436
<i>Come on, teach me tonight</i>

741
00:51:08,840 --> 00:51:11,070
<i>Starting with the ABC of it</i>

742
00:51:12,200 --> 00:51:15,909
<i>Right down to the XYZ of it</i>

743
00:51:16,120 --> 00:51:20,989
<i>Help me solve</i>
<i>the mystery of it, yeah</i>

744
00:51:21,120 --> 00:51:23,270
<i>I wanna be taught tonight</i>

745
00:51:24,520 --> 00:51:27,717
<i>The cold sky's a blackboard</i>

746
00:51:27,840 --> 00:51:29,353
<i>High above me</i>

747
00:51:29,480 --> 00:51:33,075
<i>If a shooting star goes by</i>

748
00:51:33,200 --> 00:51:36,829
<i>I'll use that star</i>
<i>To write "I love you"</i>

749
00:51:37,640 --> 00:51:39,631
<i>A thousand times across the sky...</i>

750
00:51:43,320 --> 00:51:44,753
Hi.

751
00:51:51,720 --> 00:51:54,154
Still trying to read this book?

752
00:51:57,880 --> 00:51:59,836
What?

753
00:52:15,040 --> 00:52:17,190
<i>... Come on, teach me tonight</i>

754
00:52:19,960 --> 00:52:22,520
<i>My baby, baby, baby, yeah</i>

755
00:52:22,640 --> 00:52:25,712
<i>Come on, teach me tonight, yeah</i>

756
00:52:25,840 --> 00:52:27,478
<i>I want to learn</i>

757
00:52:27,600 --> 00:52:30,592
<i>Teach me, hey</i>
<i>Teach me</i>

758
00:52:31,160 --> 00:52:33,435
<i>Teach me, teach me, teach me...</i>

759
00:52:40,920 --> 00:52:44,708
Hello, JJ.
Billie called me. Is she here?

760
00:52:44,840 --> 00:52:46,193
Yeah, she is.

761
00:52:48,040 --> 00:52:52,716
- You want to let her know I'm here?
- Yeah.

762
00:52:52,840 --> 00:52:55,479
I don't see the problem.

763
00:52:55,600 --> 00:52:59,036
There are competing
economic considerations...

764
00:52:59,280 --> 00:53:01,032
Boys, don't jerk me around.

765
00:53:01,160 --> 00:53:04,994
If you're gonna help me out,
I need to know and I need to know now.

766
00:53:05,120 --> 00:53:08,157
Harry's blunt about it,
but a lot is riding on this.

767
00:53:08,280 --> 00:53:09,998
He's the principal employer in the area.

768
00:53:10,120 --> 00:53:12,680
- Sorry, I was looking for Billie.
- She's not...

769
00:53:12,800 --> 00:53:17,112
Senator Hedges, hi! Paul Verrall.
I interviewed you.

770
00:53:17,240 --> 00:53:19,196
- I loved what you did.
- Thanks.

771
00:53:19,320 --> 00:53:22,437
Here she is. I think you two
would be more comfortable...

772
00:53:22,560 --> 00:53:25,393
Billie,
would you make this poor man a drink?

773
00:53:25,520 --> 00:53:27,670
Nice to see you again, Paul.

774
00:53:27,800 --> 00:53:29,438
Nice to see you, gentlemen.

775
00:53:29,560 --> 00:53:31,835
Good to see you again.

776
00:53:31,960 --> 00:53:34,155
- Harry.
- Hey, kid.

777
00:53:39,520 --> 00:53:42,990
- What did he mean, he interviewed you?
- He's a reporter.

778
00:53:43,120 --> 00:53:44,872
He's doing a puff piece on Harry.

779
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:47,878
Not now he's seen him
alone in a room with all of us.

780
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:50,150
Thanks for coming so quick.

781
00:53:51,120 --> 00:53:53,031
- Quickly.
- Quickly.

782
00:53:53,160 --> 00:53:56,516
Billie, Harry's got six senators in there.

783
00:53:56,640 --> 00:53:58,631
So? He's had 'em before.

784
00:53:58,760 --> 00:54:01,354
Senators don't usually make house calls.

785
00:54:01,480 --> 00:54:05,393
Harry gets people to do things
they don't usually do.

786
00:54:05,520 --> 00:54:07,272
Want to know the trick I came up with

787
00:54:07,400 --> 00:54:09,960
to remember the amendments
to the Constitution?

788
00:54:10,080 --> 00:54:12,958
- Billie?
- What?

789
00:54:13,080 --> 00:54:15,753
You've worked really hard
to make yourself smart.

790
00:54:18,040 --> 00:54:19,678
But?

791
00:54:19,800 --> 00:54:23,554
A smart person
knows who she's living with.

792
00:54:26,240 --> 00:54:29,596
Gentlemen, I really don't want you
to worry about this...

793
00:54:34,040 --> 00:54:35,996
That's beautiful.

794
00:54:38,360 --> 00:54:39,429
OK.

795
00:54:39,560 --> 00:54:41,869
I think you'll enjoy <i>David Copperfield.</i>

796
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:44,309
Anything by Dickens is wonderful.

797
00:54:44,440 --> 00:54:46,396
What is this crap?

798
00:54:46,800 --> 00:54:48,950
It's Haydn, Op. 111.

799
00:54:49,080 --> 00:54:52,755
- It's a classical piece, Harry.
- Classic piece of shit if you ask me.

800
00:54:52,880 --> 00:54:54,029
I like it.

801
00:54:54,160 --> 00:54:56,116
It's good before bed.

802
00:54:57,200 --> 00:54:59,953
So, the Fifth Amendment
to the Constitution

803
00:55:00,080 --> 00:55:02,753
says that you can't testify
against yourself.

804
00:55:02,880 --> 00:55:06,475
How would that even work?
It seems physically impossible.

805
00:55:06,600 --> 00:55:12,038
- You're teaching her about the Fifth?
- Well, the Constitution. I thought...

806
00:55:12,160 --> 00:55:14,435
It's not your job to think.
Get her to think.

807
00:55:14,560 --> 00:55:17,358
- Harry!
- It's OK, Billie.

808
00:55:17,480 --> 00:55:19,471
First of all, she knows how to think.

809
00:55:19,600 --> 00:55:21,079
And second, she...

810
00:55:21,200 --> 00:55:24,510
I need her so she can talk at parties,
not pass some ancient history test.

811
00:55:24,640 --> 00:55:28,519
You think the Constitution
is ancient history?

812
00:55:28,640 --> 00:55:31,950
- Work on her, not me.
- No extra charge.

813
00:55:32,080 --> 00:55:33,832
I don't need nothing you could tell me.

814
00:55:33,960 --> 00:55:37,111
- There's a lot he could tell you.
- I'll bet!

815
00:55:37,240 --> 00:55:40,152
Who's Tom Paine, for instance?

816
00:55:40,280 --> 00:55:44,159
What do I care? If he's not buying
from me, why should I care?

817
00:55:44,280 --> 00:55:47,431
You're so smart,
who's Dave Righetti?

818
00:55:48,040 --> 00:55:50,235
Left-handed pitcher for the Giants,

819
00:55:50,360 --> 00:55:53,318
pitched a no-hitter for the Yanks in '83.

820
00:55:53,440 --> 00:55:56,193
So what are you, some kind of genius?

821
00:55:56,760 --> 00:55:59,832
- No.
- I fire geniuses every day.

822
00:56:01,400 --> 00:56:04,631
- Clearly.
- The more I see you, the less I like you.

823
00:56:06,520 --> 00:56:10,638
Is that the way you talk
to your senator friends, too, Harry?

824
00:56:16,800 --> 00:56:18,552
I'm gonna tell you this once.

825
00:56:19,800 --> 00:56:22,951
Don't push your luck.
Stay out of my business.

826
00:56:23,080 --> 00:56:25,071
Keep your eye on
what I pay you to keep it on,

827
00:56:25,200 --> 00:56:26,758
or I'll tear it out of your head.

828
00:56:30,280 --> 00:56:32,635
I got to go, Billie.

829
00:56:36,160 --> 00:56:38,628
Just remember, four-eyes.

830
00:56:38,760 --> 00:56:41,069
Any time I want,
I can knock your block off.

831
00:56:48,200 --> 00:56:49,997
See you later, Billie.

832
00:56:50,120 --> 00:56:52,076
Bye.

833
00:56:57,040 --> 00:57:00,828
- Ed said not to forget these.
- That guy's starting to bug me.

834
00:57:00,960 --> 00:57:05,112
Here, doll, sign these papers.

835
00:57:05,240 --> 00:57:08,312
What exactly are you doing
in Washington, Harry?

836
00:57:08,440 --> 00:57:11,989
Telling you to sign those papers,
and you're going to sign them.

837
00:57:12,120 --> 00:57:15,271
I don't want to do anything
that's against the law.

838
00:57:15,400 --> 00:57:17,356
I am the law.

839
00:57:19,360 --> 00:57:23,239
It seems to me by signing these,
it makes me some kind of a partner.

840
00:57:23,360 --> 00:57:25,237
A silent partner.

841
00:57:25,360 --> 00:57:27,430
- So?
- So shut up!

842
00:57:27,560 --> 00:57:29,596
You know what your problem is, Harry?

843
00:57:29,720 --> 00:57:31,756
You're not just rude, you're...

844
00:57:31,880 --> 00:57:33,916
...flagrant about it.

845
00:57:45,080 --> 00:57:47,196
You've been reading de Tocqueville.

846
00:57:47,320 --> 00:57:50,517
Well, yeah!
After we talked on your show,

847
00:57:50,640 --> 00:57:54,030
I figured it was pretty bad that
I hadn't read such an important book.

848
00:57:54,160 --> 00:57:55,832
So I read it.

849
00:57:56,880 --> 00:57:59,314
What was your favourite part?

850
00:57:59,600 --> 00:58:04,116
Well, I'm not sure it's a book
where you can have a favourite part.

851
00:58:04,240 --> 00:58:05,992
Yes, you can. I did.

852
00:58:06,120 --> 00:58:07,553
I liked when he said,

853
00:58:07,680 --> 00:58:12,549
"What is not yet done is only what
we have not yet attempted to do."

854
00:58:12,680 --> 00:58:14,557
It made me feel good.

855
00:58:14,680 --> 00:58:16,591
So, what part did you like?

856
00:58:18,480 --> 00:58:20,914
- May I be honest?
- Yeah.

857
00:58:22,040 --> 00:58:23,758
I haven't read it.

858
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:30,197
But you said it was the one book
on democracy worth reading.

859
00:58:30,320 --> 00:58:31,833
That's what everybody says.

860
00:58:31,960 --> 00:58:36,954
That's all anybody knows
about de Tocqueville. Except you.

861
00:58:37,080 --> 00:58:41,153
Well, it's not so bad
once you stop falling asleep.

862
00:58:43,280 --> 00:58:46,670
Hi! I couldn't wait
to see how it went.

863
00:58:46,800 --> 00:58:48,677
So, she's stupid.

864
00:58:48,800 --> 00:58:52,156
Well, all I mean is,
I didn't feel stupid myself.

865
00:58:52,280 --> 00:58:54,236
She hadn't never read the book.

866
00:58:54,360 --> 00:58:56,237
- You're kidding!
- No.

867
00:58:56,360 --> 00:58:59,318
People always pretend
to be smarter than they are.

868
00:58:59,440 --> 00:59:01,317
I don't.

869
00:59:01,440 --> 00:59:04,398
I know, Billie.
You're an honest one.

870
00:59:04,520 --> 00:59:08,274
When I just said, "She hadn't
never read it," that wasn't right.

871
00:59:08,400 --> 00:59:10,391
It was a double negative but...

872
00:59:10,520 --> 00:59:13,478
Come on! You told me you'd tell me
when I made a mistake.

873
00:59:13,600 --> 00:59:17,513
A person who reads de Tocqueville should
know not to do no double negatives.

874
00:59:17,640 --> 00:59:19,995
Yes, ma'am!

875
00:59:24,760 --> 00:59:27,320
Smells good in here, doesn't it?

876
00:59:29,200 --> 00:59:32,988
If I'd known art smelled this good,
I would have come a long time ago!

877
00:59:42,640 --> 00:59:45,996
God, it's so small but it's like
it's bigger than the whole room.

878
00:59:47,960 --> 00:59:51,509
Van Gogh painted this
near the end of his life.

879
00:59:54,960 --> 00:59:59,238
What a shame that he was never
recognised while he was still living.

880
00:59:59,360 --> 01:00:01,316
Don't you think?

881
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:06,549
My mother died
when I was little and...

882
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:10,639
...my dad raised me and my brothers.

883
01:00:12,120 --> 01:00:14,714
And he loved us so much, but...

884
01:00:14,840 --> 01:00:18,310
I never knew a world like that.

885
01:00:29,840 --> 01:00:32,877
Why didn't you ever kiss me again?

886
01:00:35,720 --> 01:00:37,597
Well, it's complicated.

887
01:00:37,720 --> 01:00:42,396
What's complicated? Either you kiss me
or you don't, and you didn't.

888
01:00:42,520 --> 01:00:44,476
Billie, I'm working for Harry.

889
01:00:44,600 --> 01:00:47,956
And I'm writing a story about him,
and you're living with him.

890
01:00:48,080 --> 01:00:51,117
Then why did you kiss me the first time?

891
01:00:54,720 --> 01:00:56,676
I made a mistake.

892
01:00:58,480 --> 01:01:00,436
Gee, sorry.

893
01:01:02,240 --> 01:01:05,550
Billie. Billie, it's not about you.

894
01:01:05,680 --> 01:01:07,636
It's about ethics.

895
01:01:09,320 --> 01:01:13,029
If I get involved with you,
I'm no different than Harry.

896
01:01:13,160 --> 01:01:16,994
I don't want to use you like Harry
uses senators to get what he wants.

897
01:01:21,040 --> 01:01:23,429
You're crazy about me, aren't you?

898
01:01:26,480 --> 01:01:28,436
Yes.

899
01:01:29,640 --> 01:01:32,393
That's why you get so mad at Harry.

900
01:01:35,360 --> 01:01:37,874
I don't hate Harry.

901
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:43,199
I hate his kind of life.
What he does, what he stands for.

902
01:01:43,320 --> 01:01:47,074
He's never thought about
anybody else in the world but himself.

903
01:01:47,200 --> 01:01:49,077
Who does?

904
01:01:49,200 --> 01:01:51,998
Oh, God, Billie, millions of people do.

905
01:01:52,120 --> 01:01:53,917
The whole damn history of the world

906
01:01:54,040 --> 01:01:57,589
is the story of the fight
between the selfish and the unselfish.

907
01:01:57,720 --> 01:01:59,870
Where do I fit in?

908
01:02:02,400 --> 01:02:04,436
I honestly don't know.

909
01:02:05,400 --> 01:02:08,676
You still think I'm the kind of person
that goes with Harry?

910
01:02:08,800 --> 01:02:11,792
You're still with him, aren't you?

911
01:02:13,080 --> 01:02:14,957
Billie, come on, now.

912
01:02:15,880 --> 01:02:17,757
Be fair.

913
01:02:17,880 --> 01:02:20,189
You told me
that all you wanted out of life

914
01:02:20,320 --> 01:02:22,880
was a mink coat
and a TV that fit in your purse.

915
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:27,391
Yeah, but that's why I did
all this learning. To change!

916
01:02:27,800 --> 01:02:29,392
And it didn't make a difference.

917
01:02:29,520 --> 01:02:33,115
- You don't think you're different?
- I do, sure.

918
01:02:33,240 --> 01:02:36,596
But you don't.
You still see me the same as I was.

919
01:02:37,440 --> 01:02:40,113
In that way,
you're no different from Harry.

920
01:02:40,240 --> 01:02:42,071
How can you say that?

921
01:02:42,200 --> 01:02:45,749
He still thinks I'm a bimbo from Vegas
and so do you.

922
01:02:45,880 --> 01:02:46,756
No, I don't.

923
01:02:46,880 --> 01:02:50,270
I've never gone through
anything like this for anybody.

924
01:02:50,400 --> 01:02:54,871
Last night, I started thinking and
I couldn't fall asleep for ten minutes.

925
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:56,956
Billie, wait.

926
01:03:00,360 --> 01:03:03,716
How come I feel
like I don't fit in any more?

927
01:03:03,840 --> 01:03:08,072
Tell me why am I so unhappy
with everything that I used to want.

928
01:03:09,720 --> 01:03:11,517
Let me tell you something, Paul.

929
01:03:11,640 --> 01:03:15,155
I don't know about
all this book stuff and ethics.

930
01:03:15,280 --> 01:03:18,033
But I do know
it only takes you so far.

931
01:03:18,160 --> 01:03:22,312
And after that, you have to go on
what you feel, not on what you know.

932
01:03:23,440 --> 01:03:25,237
But I know one thing.

933
01:03:25,360 --> 01:03:29,717
There's a time between a guy and a girl
when it either comes off or it doesn't.

934
01:03:29,840 --> 01:03:32,434
And if it doesn't then, it never does.

935
01:03:34,400 --> 01:03:38,029
- Maybe we haven't gotten to our time.
- No, we did.

936
01:03:38,160 --> 01:03:40,993
You just dropped the ball.

937
01:03:54,000 --> 01:03:56,719
For all our griping, we're a lucky group.

938
01:03:56,840 --> 01:03:59,479
We got food, a roof, friends around us.

939
01:03:59,600 --> 01:04:05,311
Watching the tube the other day, I saw
how many homeless are veterans.

940
01:04:05,440 --> 01:04:07,271
They ought to tack this
on the Constitution.

941
01:04:07,400 --> 01:04:11,279
If you risk your life for your country,
you ought to have a home.

942
01:04:11,400 --> 01:04:13,834
The Sixth Amendment to the Constitution

943
01:04:13,960 --> 01:04:17,111
says you can't be deprived of property
without compensation.

944
01:04:17,240 --> 01:04:21,153
It's too bad they didn't offer
that protection to veterans.

945
01:04:21,280 --> 01:04:23,236
That's in the Fifth Amendment.

946
01:04:25,600 --> 01:04:28,273
No, no, I think it's the Sixth.

947
01:04:28,400 --> 01:04:31,756
- Don't pay any attention to her.
- Actually, you're both wrong.

948
01:04:31,880 --> 01:04:34,269
Property compensation
is the Seventh.

949
01:04:34,400 --> 01:04:35,992
- It's the Fifth.
- Billie!

950
01:04:36,120 --> 01:04:39,795
The Fifth is where you don't
incriminate yourself. Jesus!

951
01:04:39,920 --> 01:04:41,956
Actually, both senators are wrong.

952
01:04:42,080 --> 01:04:44,469
Billie's right.

953
01:04:46,120 --> 01:04:47,075
Thanks.

954
01:04:47,200 --> 01:04:51,990
There's a bunch of clauses in the Fifth.
One of them is property compensation.

955
01:04:52,120 --> 01:04:54,111
The Sixth
is the right to a speedy trial.

956
01:04:54,240 --> 01:04:59,109
You put us to shame.
Are you a constitutional lawyer?

957
01:05:00,400 --> 01:05:04,871
No. I'm a student, I guess.

958
01:05:05,520 --> 01:05:09,718
I have a hard time keeping them
straight so I make up little tricks.

959
01:05:09,840 --> 01:05:13,469
Like a... mnemonic device?

960
01:05:13,600 --> 01:05:16,797
I didn't buy anything for it,
if that's what you mean.

961
01:05:16,920 --> 01:05:19,753
- Like I was saying...
- What's your trick?

962
01:05:19,880 --> 01:05:21,552
Really?

963
01:05:21,680 --> 01:05:23,671
